raw_response:
The game is analyzed by backward induction on the subsets of active players, determining optimal actions and win probabilities in every state. A state is defined by the set \(S\) of active players and whose turn it is; the turn order is the fixed cycle \(A\to B\to C\to A\ldots\), skipping any player not in \(S\).

When \(|S|=2\) the optimal action is always to challenge the remaining opponent (passing is strictly dominated). The resulting win probabilities are:
- \(AB\), \(A\)'s turn: \(P_A=3/7\), \(P_B=4/7\);
- \(AB\), \(B\)'s turn: \(P_A=1/7\), \(P_B=6/7\);
- \(AC\), \(A\)'s turn: \(P_A=1/3\), \(P_C=2/3\);
- \(AC\), \(C\)'s turn: \(P_A=0\), \(P_C=1\);
- \(BC\), \(B\)'s turn: \(P_B=2/3\), \(P_C=1/3\);
- \(BC\), \(C\)'s turn: \(P_B=0\), \(P_C=1\).

When \(S=\{A,B,C\}\) the same procedure yields unique optimal actions. On \(C\)'s turn, \(C\) eliminates \(B\) (the stronger remaining threat), moving to state \(AC\) on \(A\)'s turn; consequently
\[
P_A(ABC_C)=1/3,\qquad P_B(ABC_C)=0,\qquad P_C(ABC_C)=2/3.
\]
On \(B\)'s turn, \(B\) challenges \(C\). With probability \(2/3\) the move succeeds and the game reaches \(AB\) on \(A\)'s turn; with probability \(1/3\) it fails and the game reaches \(ABC_C\). The resulting probabilities are
\[
P_A(ABC_B)=25/63,\qquad P_B(ABC_B)=8/21,\qquad P_C(ABC_B)=2/9.
\]
On \(A\)'s turn the three possible actions produce the following values for \(P_A\):
- challenge \(B\): \(50/189\);
- challenge \(C\): \(59/189\);
- pass: \(25/63=75/189\).

Hence the unique optimum for \(A\) is to pass, after which the continuation value is exactly \(25/63\). All assumptions about later players' behavior are self-consistent with these choices.

Final Answer: pass; 25/63

